The Special Olympics transform the unique identity of athletes with intellectual disabilities and the perception of anyone watching the competition.
For those of you who do not know, the Special Olympics are aimed at athletes with intellectual disabilities.
The Special Olympics are separate from the Paralympic and Olympic Games.
We offer high-quality sports programs all year round for individuals with intellectual disabilities, which changes lives and perceptions.
This movement has changed my life and that of so many others.
And this has changed the way the world sees people with intellectual disabilities.
I was born epileptic and with an intellectual disability.
Growing up, I played hockey until I was 12 years old.
The more I grew up, the more I felt that it was harder to keep up with others, and I was annoyed and frustrated.
For a while, I didn't practice any sports anymore, had no friends, and felt forgotten and sad.
There was a time when people with intellectual disabilities were hidden from society.
No one thought they could practice a sport, let alone be an important member of society.
In the 1960s, Dr. Frank Hayden, a scientist at the University of Toronto, studied the effects of regular exercise on the physical condition of children with intellectual disabilities.
Using rigorous scientific research, Dr. Hayden and other researchers concluded that it was simply the lack of opportunity to participate that led to physical fitness issues.
Many people doubted that individuals with intellectual disabilities could benefit from fitness programs and sports competitions.
But pioneers like Dr. Hayden and Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the founder of the Special Olympics, persevered, and the athletes of the Special Olympics proved them right four and a half million times.
Before I joined the Special Olympics, I was nervous because I was young, shy, and had little confidence in myself, and I didn't have many friends.
When I arrived, however, everyone encouraged me a lot, supported me, and let me be myself without being judged.
Now, I am a basketball player and a speed skater who has competed in regional and national games, and this year, finished at the Summer World Games in Los Angeles, where I was part of the very first Canadian basketball team to participate in the World Games.
I am one of over four and a half million athletes from around the world, and I have heard so many similar stories.
Being an athlete in the Special Olympics restores pride and dignity.
The Special Olympics also address important health needs.
Studies have shown that on average, men with intellectual disabilities die 13 years younger than men without, and women with intellectual disabilities die 20 years younger than women without.
The Special Olympics keep us healthy by keeping us active and engaging us in sports.
Furthermore, our coaches teach us about nutrition and health.
The Special Olympics also provide free screening tests for athletes who have difficulty communicating with their doctor or accessing medical care.
At the 2015 World Summer Games, my teammates from Team Canada and I were playing against the team from Nigeria.
The day before our game, the Nigerian basketball team came for screening at the World Games Athletes were distributed free to seven out of ten members and had the opportunity to hear clearly for the first time.
This change for them was incredible.
They were very excited, happy, and confident, as their coaches could communicate orally with them.
And they were very moved because they could hear the sounds of the basketball, the sounds of the whistle, and the enthusiastic fans in the stands - sounds that we take for granted.
The Special Olympics do more than just transform athletes in sports.
The Special Olympics transform their lives off the field.
This year, a study has shown that nearly half of adults in the United States do not know a single person with an intellectual disability, and the 44% of Americans who do not have personal contact with intellectual disabilities are significantly less tolerant and positive.
Then there is the word "R", demonstrating that individuals with intellectual disabilities are still invisible to far too many people.
People use it as a common term or an insult.
