This year, at the 2015 World Summer Games, people lined up for hours before diving into the final night of weightlifting competition.
The venue was packed that evening when my teammate Jackie Barrett, the Newfoundland Elk, lifted 297 kg and 277 kg in squats - setting huge new records at the Special Olympics.
Jackie is one of the record holders among all weightlifters from Newfoundland - not just at the Special Olympics but all weightlifters.
Jackie was a huge celebrity in Los Angeles, and ESPN tweeted live about his new record and was impressed by his performance.
Fifty years ago, few people imagined mentally disabled individuals capable of doing something like this.
This year, 60,000 spectators filled the famous LA Memorial Coliseum to watch the opening ceremonies of the World Games and applaud athletes from 165 countries from around the world.
Far from being hidden, we were applauded and celebrated.
The Special Olympics teach athletes to be confident and proud of themselves.
The Special Olympics teach the world that people with intellectual disabilities deserve respect and consideration.
Now, I have dreams and successes in my sport, great coaches, respect and dignity, better health, and I am pursuing a career as a personal trainer.
I am no longer hidden, mocked, and I am here giving a TED talk.
The world is a different place thanks to the Special Olympics, but there is still work to be done.
So the next time you see someone with intellectual disabilities, I hope you see their talent.
Next time someone uses the "R" word next to you, I hope you will tell them how hurtful it is.
